I want to start off by saying that I very rarely leave reviews. Ayat is worthy of all its praise, AND THEN SOME! This little restaurant is near and dear to my heart, and it’s the perfect addition to the neighborhood. Food is a very special tool that people have been using for centuries to share their cultures, and Ayat captivates this quality perfectly. Their menu consists of authentic Palestinian cuisine, and they execute everything with the utmost perfection. Everything that I’ve eaten from here has been fresh, beaming with flavor, and hearty. I’ve never left this place unhappy or unsatisfied. Their presentation is also spectacular. And their portions? Enough to feed two people. I almost always have left overs.  Point being: When I eat here? I feel happy. Their food actually makes me feel happy. And the staff? Wonderful people. They too, put a big smile on my face. They’re gorgeous!  For those leaving shameful fake reviews, or being untruthful about your experience, I truly hope you can find peace in your misery. It must be hard seeing a strong Palestinian woman be successful, devoted to her cause, all while maintaining her elegance and grace. It really must eat away at you knowing this restaurant has flourished, and will continue to do well. Good on Ayat for using their voice and platform to speak up for Palestine ❤️ All my love to them, and I will forever have this be my personal favorite spot in Bay Ridge.

Why choose?  —The portions are large! We ordered the mixed grill for 4, for $100, which could have fed 8 people easily. Get your whole quarantine pod together and you could have a meal for $15 a person easily.  —They don’t include a lot of the excellent bread (it’s hand-made in the restaurant) in your order, and it would be helpful to have a side order just of bread.  Basically, it’s excellent all around, they’re very helpful and patient.

We had a great experience with Ayat. We wanted to get catered food to welcome a new family member originally from Palestine, and Ayat and the rest of the staff were very helpful in explaining the dishes and our options. We wound up ordering the mixed grill, several other main dishes, and appetizers and breads. All were delicious; all were packed very well and made it over to NJ from Brooklyn and stayed hot. The grilled meats were juicy and flavorful despite their travels, and there was a panoply of unique flavors among all the dishes that was wonderful. They checked in with us the morning when we were to pick up the food to check our arrival time, and then grilled the breads last minute so they were at their hottest and freshest. And finally, they threw in a selection of Middle Eastern desserts so that we could have the experience of a complete meal. Ayat was particularly helpful and gracious, and the entire staff was friendly and accommodating. Our family (including some not-so-adventurous eaters) loved it all! I can't wait till we can go and sit in the restaurant for the immediate restaurant experience.

Ayat just opened up.  They offer Middle Eastern fare. We had a great meal there.  We split small sides of baba ghanoush ($6?), tabulah ($6).  The excellent baba ghanoush was garnished with pomegranate.  We split a large chicken kebab ($16?).  It was succulent and nicely spiced.  The most moist kebab I have ever had. And I have had a chicken kebab a lot.  We like to ask for salad instead of rice with a main dish. The platter came with a good salad with tabulah, baba ghanoush and hummus.  They serve water in a pottery vase with small pottery glasses.  Nice touch.  A filling meal for two came to $28.  There is a large accordion folding front windowed front wall to the street  - so it is wide open in this time when you want maximum outside ventilation. There are a few tables outside and one right inside by the huge opening to the street.  Only caveat is the two times we visited serving staff were not wearing masks.  Staff was helpful.  We wish Ayat well.
